    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-07-27T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-07-27T17:00:00-05:00" n="782"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d782">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">825.001 Montero, Juan/1: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Culbertson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-07-27T17:00:00-05:00"
                            >July 27, 1931—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:20 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>83. President of Senate resigned today as Vice President and, following the
                    Constitution, turned over the power to Montero, Minister of the Interior, who
                    became Vice and Acting President. Retirement of President of Senate appeases the
                    crowds, resentful at escape of Ibañez, and at the same time strengthens the
                    situation. It is possible now that Blanquier who has held aloof will join the
                    Cabinet. Ibañez is now in Argentina.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Culbertson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
